Q1¶

$$P(\omega_1|x)=\frac{P(\omega_1)P(x|\omega_1)}{P(x)}$$$$P(\omega_2|x)=\frac{P(\omega_2)P(x|\omega_2)}{P(x)}$$$$P(x)=P(\omega_1)P(x|\omega_1)+P(\omega_2)P(x|\omega_2)$$$$P(\omega_1) = P(\omega_2) = 0.5$$$$P(x|\omega_i)= \frac{1}{\pi b}\frac{1}{1+(\frac{x-a_i}{b})^2}$$

def cauchy_dist(x, a, b):
    return 1/((np.pi*b)*(1+((x-a)/b)**2))

Naive Bayes and Optimal Bayes Classifier:¶

Bayes Rule : $$ P(Y = i|x) = \frac{P(x|Y=i) * P(Y=i)}{P(x)} \qquad \forall i$$

When likelihood distribution is not known:¶

Optimal Bayes classifier:¶

Optimal bayes classifier chooses the class that has greatest posteriori probability of occurrence. To calculate posterior probability we can use the given formula ($I(x_{i}=x \land y_{i}=y)=1$ if $x_{i}=x$ and $y_{i}=y$ and 0 otherwise.): $$ p(y|x) = \frac{p(y,x)}{p(x)} = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}I(x_{i}=x \land y_{i}=y)}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}I(x_{i}=x)} \qquad,\quad $$

  • Optimal bayes classifier has high computational cost. For example if there are k classes, for classifying a new data point x with d features and n different possible values per each feature, we have to compute $k(n^d-1)$ parameters.
  • Optimal bayes classifier is only useful whene there are many training vectors with the same identical features as x. But in high dimensional spaces or with continuous x, as p(y,x) and p(x) converge to zero it is not possible to use optimal bayes classifier.
Naive Bayes classifier:¶

The Naive Bayes classifier approximates the optimal Bayes classifier by looking at the empirical distribution and by assuming independence of predictors. Naive Bayes assumes feature values are independent given the label, thus: $$p(x|y) = \prod_{j=1}^{d}p(x_{j}|y)\quad for \quad x=(x_{1},...,x_{d}) $$

When likelihood distribution is known:¶

When likelihood is known the posterior probability can be directly calculated by multiplying the prior and likelihood.

Bayes Classfier¶

class BayesClassifier():
    def __init__(self, target_col):
        self.priors = {}
        self.target_col = target_col
        self.attributes_dict = {}
    
    def mean(self, values):   
        return sum(values)/float(len(values))

    def stdev(self, values):
        avg = self.mean(values)
        variance = sum([((x-avg)**2) for x in values])/len(values)
        return variance**0.5
    
    def univariate_gaussian_probability(self, x, avg, std): 
        return (1/(math.sqrt(2*math.pi)*std)) * math.exp(-(math.pow(x-avg, 2)/(2*math.pow(std, 2))))
 
    def multivariate_gaussian_probability(self,x, mean_vec, cov_mat): 
        x = np.atleast_2d(x).T
        cov_det, cov_inv = np.linalg.det(cov_mat), np.linalg.inv(cov_mat)    
        temp = np.exp(-.5 * (x - mean_vec).T @ cov_inv @ (x - mean_vec))
        return (2 * np.pi) ** (-x.size/2) * cov_det ** (-1/2) * temp
    
    
    def train(self, X_train, Y_train, oneVsAllLabel):
        total_data_count = len(X_train)
        train_df = pd.DataFrame(X_train)
        train_df[self.target_col] = list(Y_train)
        df1, df2 = train_df[(mask:=train_df[self.target_col] == oneVsAllLabel)], train_df[~mask]
        train_dfs = [df1, df2]
        labels = [True, False]
        for label, df in zip(labels, train_dfs):
            self.attributes_dict[label] = self.get_distribution_statistics(df)
            self.priors[label] = len(df)/total_data_count
            
    
    def predict(self, x_test):
        test_df = pd.DataFrame(x_test)
        predictions = []
        for i in range(len(test_df)):
            prediction_dict = self.calculate_class_probabilities(test_df.iloc[i])
            predictions.append(max(prediction_dict, key=prediction_dict.get))
        return predictions

Gaussian Optimal Bayes Classifier¶

In [80]:
class GaussianOptimalBayesClassifier(BayesClassifier):
    def __init__(self, target_col):
        super().__init__(target_col)
        
    def get_distribution_statistics(self,dataset):
        """
            returns mean vector and covariance matrix of each class
        """
        feature_cols = list(dataset.columns)[:-1]
        mean_vector = [self.mean(dataset[column]) for column in feature_cols]  
        mean_vector = np.atleast_2d(mean_vector).T   
        cov_matrix = np.cov(np.array([dataset[column] for column in feature_cols]), bias=True)
        cov_matrix = np.atleast_2d(cov_matrix)
        return [mean_vector, cov_matrix]
    
    def calculate_class_probabilities(self,test_row):
        probabilities = {}
        for classValue in self.attributes_dict.keys():
            probabilities[classValue] = self.priors[classValue]
            mean_vec, cov_mat = self.attributes_dict[classValue][0], self.attributes_dict[classValue][1]
            probabilities[classValue] *= self.multivariate_gaussian_probability(test_row, mean_vec, cov_mat)
        return probabilities

Gaussian Naive Bayes Classifier¶

All features are considered independent. Also, it is assumed that continuous values associated with each feature are distributed according to a normal distribution.

In [92]:
class GaussianNBClassifier(BayesClassifier):
    
    def __init__(self, target_col):
        super().__init__(target_col)
       
    def get_distribution_statistics(self, dataset):
        """
            return each feature's mean and std
        """
        feature_cols = list(dataset.columns)[:-1]
        feature_atts = [(self.mean(dataset[column]), self.stdev(dataset[column])) for column in feature_cols]    
        return feature_atts
    
    def calculate_class_probabilities(self, test_row):
        probabilities = {}
        for classValue in self.attributes_dict.keys():
            probabilities[classValue] = self.priors[classValue]
            for i in range(len(self.attributes_dict[classValue])):
                avg, std_dev = self.attributes_dict[classValue][i][0], self.attributes_dict[classValue][i][1]
                probabilities[classValue] *= self.univariate_gaussian_probability(test_row[i], avg, std_dev)
        return probabilities
Splitting Data¶
In [82]:
import random
def stratified_train_test_split(df, target_col, oneVsAllLabel, test_size=0.2, seed=76):
        random.seed(seed)
        label1_inds = df.index[df[target_col] == oneVsAllLabel].tolist()
        label0_inds = df.index[df[target_col] != oneVsAllLabel].tolist()
        train_label1_inds = random.sample( label1_inds, int((1-test_size)*len(label1_inds))+1)
        train_label0_inds = random.sample( label0_inds, int((1-test_size)*len(label0_inds)))
        
        test_label1_inds = [i for i in label1_inds if i not in train_label1_inds]
        test_label0_inds = [i for i in label0_inds if i not in train_label0_inds]
        
        X_train = np.array(df.iloc[:,1:].loc[train_label1_inds+train_label0_inds])
        Y_train = np.array(df.iloc[:,0].loc[train_label1_inds+train_label0_inds])
        x_test = np.array(df.iloc[:,1:].loc[test_label1_inds+test_label0_inds])
        y_test = np.array(df.iloc[:,0].loc[test_label1_inds+test_label0_inds])
        return X_train, Y_train, x_test, y_test
Evaluating Model¶
In [83]:
def get_metrics(y_true, predictions, pos_label):
    TP = sum([1 for i in range(len(y_true)) if y_true[i] == predictions[i] and  predictions[i]==pos_label])
    TN = sum([1 for i in range(len(y_true)) if y_true[i] == predictions[i] and  predictions[i]!=pos_label])
    FP = sum([1 for i in range(len(y_true)) if y_true[i] != predictions[i] and  predictions[i]==pos_label])
    FN = sum([1 for i in range(len(y_true)) if y_true[i] != predictions[i] and  predictions[i]!=pos_label])       
    return TP, TN, FP, FN
    
def evaluate_model(y_true, y_pred, oneVsAllLabel):
        TP, TN, FP, FN =  get_metrics(y_true, y_pred, pos_label=oneVsAllLabel)
        print('Recall: %.3f' % (TP / (FN + TP)))
        print('Precision: %.3f' % (TP / (FP + TP)))
        print('Accuracy: %.3f' % ((TP + TN)/ (TP + FN + TN + FP)))
        
        
def plot_confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred, oneVsAllLabel):
    TP, TN, FP, FN =  get_metrics(y_true, y_pred, oneVsAllLabel)
    confusion_mat = np.array([[TP,FN], [FP,TN]])
    group_names = ['True Pos','False Neg','False Pos','True Neg']
    group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}".format(value) for value in
                    confusion_mat.flatten()]

    labels = [f"{v1}\n{v2}" for v1, v2 in
                zip(group_names,group_counts)]

    labels = np.asarray(labels).reshape(2,2)

    ax = sns.heatmap(confusion_mat, annot=labels, fmt='', cmap='Blues')
    
    ax.set_title('Confusion Matrix\n\n');
    ax.set_xlabel('\nPredicted Values')
    ax.set_ylabel('Actual Values ');
    ax.xaxis.set_ticklabels(['True','False'])
    ax.yaxis.set_ticklabels(['True','False'])
    plt.show()

from numpy import asarray
import os
from PIL import Image
import random
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

def load_data(data_dir):
    images = []
    labels = []
    for filename in os.listdir(data_dir):
        image = Image.open(os.path.join(data_dir,filename))
        images.append(asarray(image))
        labels.append(filename[0])
    return images,labels

Classification model¶

we want to classify any image as being green or blue in overall color. First we calculate per-channel image mean for each image. Then for each image we compare its green channel mean with blue channel mean. If green channel mean is greater we classify image as Jungle and Sea otherwise.

In [17]:
def predict(images):
    gChannel = [(np.sum(img[:,:,1])/(img.shape[0]*img.shape[1])) for img in images]
    bChannel = [(np.sum(img[:,:,2])/(img.shape[0]*img.shape[1])) for img in images]
    predictions = [1 if gChannel[i]>bChannel[i] else 0 for i in range(0,len(gChannel))]
    return predictions

def print_missclassified_samples(images,y_true,y_pred):
   
    FN_ind = random.choice([i for i in range(len(y_true)) if y_true[i] == 1 and y_pred[i]==0 ])
    FP_ind = random.choice([i for i in range(len(y_true)) if y_true[i] == 0 and y_pred[i]==1 ])
    reverse_labelMap = dict(map(reversed, label_map.items()))
    title1='True label:'+str(Rlabel_map[y_true[FN_ind]])+',   Predicted label:'+str(Rlabel_map[y_pred[FN_ind]])
    title2='True label:'+str(Rlabel_map[y_true[FP_ind]])+',   Predicted label:'+str(Rlabel_map[y_pred[FP_ind]])
                                                                                           
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 7))
    fig.add_subplot(2, 1, 1)
    plt.imshow(images[FN_ind])
    plt.axis('off')
   
    plt.title(title1)
    
    fig.add_subplot(2, 1, 2)
    plt.imshow(images[FP_ind])
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.title(title2)
